  "text": "We were not actually looking for music.  We were looking for a backpack upgrade. As with every such game, inventory management inevitably becomes a mini-game of its own and it starts with how much stuff you can haul around or pick up when you’re out exploring. Welcome to Enshrouded We had gotten the first backpack ages ago, but since then had failed to find any further improvements.  This was, in part, due to how Enshrouded is laid out. The game is divided up into what one might as well think of as zones, each of which has a spire that one can unlock by solving its puzzle so it becomes a fast travel point.  Not just a fast travel point but, being a spire standing above the landscape, a launch point to glide towards various objective.  Gliding is life in Enshrouded. Gliding to catch up to Potshot Anyway, as I have been told, the initial game map was spread on more of an east-west axis, where moving eastward represented higher level content… though content levels and player levels are not as impactful as they are in a title like WoW.  We’ve had a level 15 boss kick out asses while we were levels 25-30. Since the original launch the game has had more content added.  In fact, we started playing just after the big update in November which raised the level cap to 35, added more areas, and gave us tamable pets. But we wanted the backpack update which we had read required the bard.  The bard is one of the survivors of the old order and there was a quest to find her, restore her, and get her a bed, because the first thing survivors seem to worry about is where they are going to sleep. Follow the Melody The bard was located in an area called Sunken Ancient City… and totally not Sunken Temple… in an area called the Blackmire… which it totally not the Swamp of Sorrows or anything. I had actually been to the edge of the Blackmire at one point… over a month ago… finding the first tar pool, but then had never made my way back. That is not water, that is sticky tar It was Potshot who pressed on into the Blackmire, which is in the northwest of the map, and managed to both find the spire there and solve its puzzle, which he described as the most annoying so far as Keen Games had decided what Enshrouded needed was more jumping puzzles when they did the area. Having saved us from this effort, we were able to fast travel to the spire and glide north to the Sunken Temple… City… whatever. On approach to Ancient Sunken City The image above is me gliding in after the fact.  My first glide in put me in the buildings to the southwest end of the city where I landed in a bunch of mud.  But mud is safe, even if it slows you down.  It is the tar that is a pain, and that isn’t water the city is in.  That is tar. Oh hey, tar… yeah The tar isn’t much to look at.  And it is sticky, like the mud, and will slow you down.  But it has an extra attribute, which is if you stand in it you sink.  And if you are out of stamina and cannot jump, you will sink into it and die.  So there were some issue with that. Not the first tar death But once we got out of the mud and over the tar to the main building in town, we found a locked door with the usual lights above it indicating that there were some buttons around to press in order to get through it. There are four light! No, wait, just three… It turned out the the Sunken City was a big outdoor puzzle, though the first button wasn’t too tough.  It was literally across the tar within line of sight of the door. The first button The other buttons were more of a challenge… both more hidden and requiring more jumping, climbing, and for at least one of them, a trampoline jump.  Did I mention the trampolines?  No?  So the devs decided what this area needed, on top of a lot of jumping puzzles, was trampolines. It just a trampoline Michael… Enshrouded trampolines are a little bouncier than those here on Earth, but once you get the hand of them they will get you places… or bounce you high enough that you can just glide. Anyway, after some searching, a couple of untimely deaths, a bit of fighting, and some trampoline fun, we found all three buttons.  The door was now open.  We would now delve into that area “deep below Sunken Ancient City” mention in the quest, and who could tell what perils that would entail.  Indoor trampolines and cracked skulls maybe? Alas, that part was a bit oversold.  Once the doors were open and we took the stairs down to the basement level, there was just the survivor capsule with the bard in it.  We had found her. The survivor capsule was waiting for us We opened it up and then had to head back to our base to deploy her… and, of course, find her a bed.  I had to make a new bed for her and our main house is filling up with survivors. Once the bard was set we were able to open up her crafting options and were rewarded with a selection of interesting options. The top bard crafting options At the top of the list were the medium and large backpack upgrades.  We couldn’t actually make the medium backpack because it required reptile leather, which we had not discovered. (Lots of it in the Blackmire, but we had only just arrived.)  But that was fine, because the large backpack was better and we had all the ingredients for that.  The large added two more rows to our inventory, a welcome addition of space. There were also a bunch of new decorations available, including some pictures to hang.  (Are those Timone and Pumba in the lower right?)  That all boosts the comfort level of our base. But in the middle were instruments.  I quickly made a flute, which just required a bone, and gave it a try. The dog critiquing my style It turns out, when you put an instrument on your action bar and activate it, you are able to play music.  You are limited to the selection of songs you have found in the world, but that is still pretty neat. More fun still is that once somebody starts playing, you can join in with them on the song they have chosen, so you can all play together.  And everybody who plays adds to the comfort level of the location.  And the higher the comfort level, the longer your rested buff lasts. Three musicians adding +1 to comfort each It isn’t quite a LOTRO level experience, where one of my favorite idle tasks it to stand on a corner in Bree and playing selections from They Might Be Giants and The Doors.  But maybe someday there will be a more free-form music system.  The game is still in Early Access after all. The group playing for an audience… damn cat is putting his two cents in It is a bit odd that you have to sit down to play.  But there are also some ornate instruments recipes out in the world.  Maybe you need those to go professional and play standing up.  We’ll see.",
